<TEXT>
bean soup that enduring congressional culinary tradition has 
been on the menu of the united states senate restaurant for most of 
the days of this century every day for the last 85 years at least 
but being on the menu does not necessarily mean being on the 
stove or on the table 
and one day 45 years ago senate republican leader bob dole 
recalled the bean soup pots stopped bubbling for the first time 
ever 
even though bean soup was on the menu that day at 10 cents a 
cup 15 cents a bowl it wasnt cooking on the stove dole said 
the day was sept 14 1943 and the senate was beanless and 
therefore soupless 
this was because wartime rationing had slashed the senates 
supply of white michigan beans dole explained 
somehow by the next day more beans were found and bowls of 
bean soup have been ladled up without any interruption ever 
since he said 
bean soup is on the menu in the senate because it was ordered to 
be there 
there is some question as to who gave the orders 
some attribute the decree to sen fred thomas dubois of idaho 
bean soup was his favorite and he presided over the senate rules 
committee which in turn presided over the senate restaurant 
therefore bean soup went on the menu 
others say the demand was made in 1903 by sen knute nelson of 
minnesota 
the rage for bean soup soon spread to the house and in 1904 
speaker joe cannon an illinois republican was outraged that the 
menu of the house restaurant did not list it 
for years cannons words on the subject were also printed on the 
house menu along with a recipe for the now famous soup 
thunderation i had my mouth set for bean soup from now on hot 
or cold rain snow or shine i want it on the menu every day 
there are many differences in the operating styles of the house 
and senate and dole said that the preparation of bean soup is one 
of them 
the senate recipe calls for adding onions braised in butter 
the house recipe calls for beans beans beans nothing but 
beans 
</TEXT>
