<TEXT>
farmers soon will be getting information from 
a new computer system devised by the agriculture department to help 
them select only the best cows for their milking herds the cream 
of the crop so to speak 
the genetic evaluation system called the animal model takes 
into account more of a cows relatives than does the older system 
the modified contemporary comparison which has been used since 
1974 the departments agricultural research service said monday 
under the new system milk production of a cows daughters will 
be considered when the mother is being evaluated and the 
evaluation of bulls based in part on the records of the males 
offspring also take into account the impact of the bulls mate on 
those offspring 
the new system will be used for the first time in dairy genetic 
evaluations to be prepared in july 1989 the report said the 
information then will be reported to dairy farmers who can use it 
to decide which cows and their calves to keep in the herd 
with this information in hand the farmer can select with more 
accuracy the calves likely to be the most efficient milk 
producers the report said 
the new system a revision of the older method was developed by 
george r wiggans a research geneticist at the agencys facility 
in beltsville md the older method was developed by duane norman 
also of beltsville 
agency work in genetic evaluation for many years has been an 
important part of a nationwide effort to improve the us dairy 
herd milk output rose from 7029 pounds per cow in 1960 to 13293 
pounds in 1986 the report said 
the trend has continued with usda figures showing the average 
milk production last year rose further to an average of 13932 
pounds 
approximately 60000 farmers participate in the improvement 
program which involves recording milk production of each cow for 
one day every month the report said information on each 
animal is compiled and sent to the animal improvement programs 
laboratory at beltsville home to approximately 39 million milk 
production records on 15 million cows 
the participating dairy farmers then receive reports on each of 
their animals the report said 
wiggans began working on the new system two years ago and in may 
1987 transferred the programs to computers at the cornell national 
supercomputer facility ithaca ny 
the cornell supercomputer has a very large memory which was 
necessary to handle all the additional details of the evaluations 
including all the relatives of milk cows he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the financial worth of burley tobacco 
producers is far below the national average for other farmers but 
they also have fewer debts an agriculture department study says 
the study by the departments economic research service involved 
273 burley tobacco farms surveyed by questionnaire in kentucky and 
tennessee for the 1984 crop the most recent information available 
it said the net worth of burley tobacco producers averaged 
130715 substantially below the 322732 average for all us 
farm producers the average farm debt for burley farms was about a 
third less than the average for all us farm producers 
according to the report which was distributed here on monday 
the farms produced an average of 23 acres of burley a cigarette 
tobacco the crop is labor intensive and required an average of 240 
hours of family and hired labor per acre or 13 hours per 100 
pounds of leaf produced in 1984 an additional 11 hours of custom 
labor was used on each acre 
the 23 acres of burley tobacco was grown on farms averaging a 
total of 122 acres of farmland 
most farms relied on nonfarm sources to supplement their 
income the report said small tobacco farms with less than 21 
acres of burley generally averaged equal sales from crops and 
livestock large tobacco farms with 6 or more acres of burley 
tobacco depended less on livestock sales receiving more than 70 
percent of their gross cash farm income from crop sales 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a new labeling law in portugal may restrict 
that countrys imports of soybean oil in favor of other kinds of 
vegetable oil according to an agriculture department trade report 
the law requires that some labels for edible vegetable oil 
containers indicated oil for dressing and frying while other 
labels indicate oil for dressing only says the departments 
foreign agricultural service 
basis for the labeling is whether the vegetable oil contains 2 
percent or less of linolenic acid which would qualify as oil for 
dressing and frying if the acid content is more than that it 
would be restricted to dressings 
sunflowerseed oil which is produced widely in the european 
economic community has the lower acid content and would qualify as 
a dualpurpose oil portugal is a member of the eec however 
soybean oil mostly from outside the eec including the united 
states has 7 percent linolenic acid and would be restricted to 
dressings the report said 
