<TEXT>
some us aid to egyptian and pakistani 
government agencies undercuts the reagan administration policy of 
helping private business and discouraging governmentowned 
enterprise congressional investigators have concluded 
a report by the general accounting office which monitors 
government spending for congress cited as an example the fact that 
the agency for international development had encouraged pakistan to 
end agricultural subsidies but also had financed 142 million in 
fertilizer and 123 million in wheat and cotton imports that the 
pakistani government sells to farmers and consumers at subsidized 
prices 
the largest of these commodity import programs benefit egypt 
and pakistan egypt has had 3 billion worth of this kind of aid 
since 1975 the report said 
official aid policy holds that goods received by 
governmentowned enterprises at subsidized prices hurt a countrys 
development because they discourage sales at market prices 
the gao also reported that the egyptian government had piled up 
325 million worth of egyptian pounds representing more than half 
the proceeds from sales of us aid goods instead of using the 
money for development projects 
the cost of this large accumulation of local currencies 
remaining idle is high in terms of missed opportunities to support 
development the report said 
the report included a memo from richard e bissell the 
assistant aid administrator saying that the egyptian government 
has tentatively promised to release about 165 million worth of the 
local currency for development efforts this year and next 
the congressional investigators said that when asked about the 
situation aid officials in pakistan and egypt acknowledged the 
detrimental effects of subsidies but said the political dimension 
of these programs limited their leverage in moving these programs 
to achieve greater impact 
