<TEXT>
a federal panel recommended today that america 
get serious about ensuring the health of its newborn citizens if 
for no better reason than to save money 
noting that more than 3 is saved for every dollar spent on 
prenatal care the institute of medicine said government health 
officials federal and local should seek out pregnant women to 
make sure they get care they and their babies need early on rather 
than wait for frail and diseased infants to be born 
the committee to study outreach for prenatal care referred to a 
1985 institute study that calculated that each dollar spent on 
providing more adequate prenatal care to lowincome poorly 
educated women could reduce total expenditures for direct medical 
care of their low birthweight infants by 338 during the first 
year of life 
joyce c lashof chairman of the committee said at a news 
conference today that expanding medicaid to cover all poor 
pregnant women would cost an additional 875 million by 1993 
but the most important fact is we would be saving 3 for every 
dollar spent so what we really need to be doing is calculating the 
net savings she said 
using that formula the medicaid expansion should result in 
net savings of 25 billion she said 
george m ryan a committee member said he is very optimistic 
that improvements will be made in prenatal care programs because 
if anything gets attention its dollars and cents 
i just dont think this nation is going to go on taking care 
of handicapped infants when we can prevent the handicaps with 
proper prenatal care said ryan 
lashof is on the faculty of the school of public health at the 
university of california in berkeley and ryan is an obstetrics and 
gynecology professor at the university of tennessee medical school 
in memphis 
the survey said the health problems encountered by a significant 
portion of newborns includes a set of financial barriers ranging 
from problems in private insurance and medicaid to the complete 
absence of health insurance 
among its recommendations the committee called for the nation 
to adopt as a new social norm the principle that all pregnant 
women not only the affluent should be provided access to 
prenatal labor and delivery and postpartum services appropriate 
to their need 
recent federal legislation authorizes states to provide prenatal 
care under medicaid for families whose income is up to 185 percent 
of the federal poverty line or more than 15000 a year for a 
family of four however it is left to the states to decide whether 
to implement the option which would result in a oneforone match 
in federal dollars 
without referring to that new state option directly the iom 
survey said too often communities organize outreach to help 
women over and around major obstacles to care rather than removing 
the obstacles themselves to fund outreach in isolation and hope 
that it alone will accomplish major improvements in the use or 
prenatal services is naive and wasteful 
the panel concluded that the solution is action rather than more 
study 
the committee specifically urges that no more research be 
conducted to demonstrate the importance of financial and other 
institutional barriers to care the report said 
the committee recommends that the current practice of 
securing funds for services under the guise of research cease 
it said the president congress and other national leaders must 
commit themselves openly and unequivocally to designing a new 
maternity care system or systems dedicated to drawing all women 
into prenatal care and providing them with an appropriate array of 
health and social services throughout pregnancy childbirth and 
the postpartum period 
