the citys economy fared much better than 
expected in the year after last octobers stock market crash 
according to a report released tuesday by state comptroller edward 
v regan 
while the securities industry clearly was hurt by the crash 
the impact has been far less severe than originally forecast 
regan said furthermore the rest of the citys economy has been 
little affected 
the report predicted that the city will gain 35000 jobs this 
year despite postcrash predictions of job losses ranging from 
10000 to 47000 
the projected 1988 loss of 7000 security industry jobs will be 
more than offset by an increase of 30000 service jobs according 
to the report even businesses closely tied to finance such as law 
and printing have shrugged off the impact of the crash 
the report listed these signs of economic vitality 
the city unemployment rate fell to 41 percent in the second 
quarter of the year the lowest since 1970 
the gross city product a measure of economic output 
posted its strongest annual growth in 20 years 34 percent for the 
12 months ending with june 
retail sales and tourism are up and the welfare caseload is 
down 
but the report warns that the city faces problems the 
securities industry could lose an another 7000 jobs next year and 
there also may be a slowdown in employment in the real estate and 
banking industries 
the report also noted that the 35000job increase for 1988 is 
smaller than the figure for each of the four previous years and 
that many of those still employed in the security industry have 
taken pay cuts 
