<TEXT>
the use of the hallucinogenic drug peyote in 
indian religious ceremonies is protected by the federal 
constitutions guarantee of religious freedom the state supreme 
court ruled today 
the decision involves two former douglas county drug counselors 
who were fired and denied jobless benefits for using peyote during 
native american church religious ceremonies 
in todays ruling the high court expanded its 1986 decision in 
which it said denying jobless benefits to the two men violated 
their constitutional rights to freely practice their religion 
the state had appealed the earlier ruling to the us supreme 
court which sent it back to the state court for a definitive 
ruling on whether peyote could be legally used in religious 
ceremonies in oregon under state criminal law 
peyote is a cactus that contains mescaline a hallucinogenic 
drug thats illegal in oregon possession of the drug is a felony 
deputy attorney general bill gary in oral arguments before the 
state supreme court earlier this year said the state has 
constitutional authority to impose a ban on all uses of peyote 
gary also argued that to permit religious use of that drug would 
open the door to all kinds of religious drug exemptions to be 
claimed in criminal trials 
the supreme court in todays decision noted that oregon laws 
against the possession of controlled substances including peyote 
make no exception for the sacramental use of peyote 
at the same time the court said that the outright prohibition 
of good faith religious use of peyote by adult members of the 
native american church would violate the first amendment directly 
and as interpreted by congress 
the ruling involved alfred smith and galen black who were fired 
from their jobs with the roseburgbased douglas county council on 
alcohol and drug abuse prevention and treatment for using peyote at 
religious ceremonies 
smith and black were denied unemployment benefits on grounds 
that they lost their jobs because of misconduct the councils 
rules forbid the use of alcohol or illegal drugs 
sueanne lovendahl a roseburg lawyer representing the two men 
argued that the use of peyote in the indian church is tightly 
controlled and that its use outside the church is a sacrilege 
</TEXT>
