<TEXT>
environmentalists are dueling with 
business and the legislature in washington state over rival ballot 
measures that each side claims is the best way to clean up toxic 
waste sites 
environmental groups back initiative 97 which would give the 
state department of ecology unilateral authority to order a site 
cleaned up impose stiff fines and pursue criminal sanctions 
against polluters who balked 
but rival ballot measure 97b backed by the business community 
and most state legislators would allow polluters time to negotiate 
a cleanup plan 
supporters say 97bs strength is it permits the state and 
industry to clean up sites together with industry bearing most of 
the expense if 97b passes it will affirm a toxic waste cleanup 
statute enacted a year ago 
initiative 97 would raise an estimated 634 million to 68 
million through a seventenths of 1 percent tax on toxic 
substances including gasoline and other refined oil products 
measure 97b would raise an estimated 51 million to 56 million 
by means of a eighttenths of 1 percent tax on hazardous 
substances this tax also would apply to refined oil products but 
unlike initiative 97 would exempt refined products exported to 
other states 
the bulk of revenues generated by either measure would go 
towards pay overhead administration and enforcement of the law 
state officials said 
backers of each measure which will be on nov 8 ballots claim 
that theirs is tougher on polluters 
the 97b proposal creates a set of bureaucratic hoops through 
which liable persons can make doe jump before it can get a site 
cleaned up said william ryan a bostonbased specialist on toxic 
waste cleanup laws no other state with toxic waste cleanup 
laws has such a convoluted response as that of the 97b proposal 
but supporters of 97b argue that the laws cooperative approach 
is its strength and the reason that ultimately it is tougher than 
97 
sen mike kreidler dolympia who helped draft the measure 
before it became law at a special legislative session a year ago 
said 97b envisions that polluters themselves will pay more than 70 
percent of negotiated cleanup costs while only a small part of 
the cost will come from the laws special tax on possessors of 
hazardous substances 
initiative 97 meanwhile would rely on a similar tax as its 
primary source of cleanup funding kreidler contended even though 
expected revenues would not begin to cover the estimated 1 billion 
to 2 billion needed to cleanse as many as 400 waste sites in the 
state 
initiative 97 kreidler said assumes that the department of 
ecology will use the tax fund for clean up and then litigate 
to recover the costs he said litigation to recover the balance 
would mean costly delays at best and possibly no money at the end 
david bricklin a main spokesman for the initiative 97 campaign 
and president of the washington environmental council countered 
that initiative 97 also relies heavily on voluntary cleanups it 
is just that ours has a significant stick attached to it to ensure 
that responsible parties step forward to clean up the sites without 
forcing the state to go to court 
supporters of 97b led by aerospace oil and timber interests 
have raised 800000 for their highly visible campaign featuring 
billboards mass mailings and tv advertising 
initiative 97 backers meanwhile have raised only 196000 and 
campaigners acknowledge that 97bs greater financial resources put 
their initiative at a disadvantage 
despite the heated debate some here believe that either measure 
would leave the state with a sound toxic waste policy 
we are not at a crossroads in state environmental policy 
said jeffrey goltz a seattle lawyer and former head of the state 
ecology division of the attorney generals office 
what is left for voters to decide this november are relatively 
minimal modifications of the approach the legislature already 
adopted he said either the initiative or the alternative 
would establish a sound proenvironment toxic waste policy for the 
state without undue burden on industry 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

