<TEXT>
income growth in the rust belt 
manufacturing states is staging a comeback after lagging behind the 
national average for most of the 1980s the government said tuesday 
the trend represents an easing in but not an end to a 
phenomenon reagan administration critics have labeled the 
bicoastal economy 
the administration has pointed with pride to the sixyear 
economic recovery the longest during peacetime since the civil 
war however critics say the nations heartland has not shared in 
the expansion 
in a report on nonfarm personal income the commerce department 
said in general states bordering the pacific and atlantic coasts 
continue to have better income growth than the states in between 
but the gap in the growth rates is narrowing 
new england a center of the boom in computer and other 
hightechnology industries still leads the nation in income 
growth from the second quarter apriljune of 1987 to second 
quarter of this year income grew 95 percent compared with 87 
percent average annual growth since the end of the last recession 
in the third quarter of 1982 
new englands growth for both periods was well above the 
national average of 77 percent in the 12 months ending in june 
the latest period for which figures are available and the 71 
percent annual average for 198287 the growth rates are not 
adjusted to remove the effects of consumer price inflation which 
was 4 percent in the 12 months ending in june 
new hampshire and massachussets posted particularly strong 
income gains of 107 percent and 99 percent respectively in the 
latest year available 
but gains in manufacturing have pushed income growth in the 
great lakes states up to average and growth in midatlantic states 
has climbed from the middle ranks to above average 
in the 12 months ending in june growth in the midatlantic 
region led by delaware and new jersey was 87 percent compared 
with 74 percent annual growth in the 198287 period 
growth in the great lakes region which lagged behind during the 
years of the overvalued dollar and exploding trade deficit was 77 
percent in the 12 months ending in june compared with 62 percent 
earlier in the decade 
meanwhile income growth in the far west and the southeast has 
cooled a bit from aboveaverage rates 
the southeast part of the sun belt boom of the early 1980s 
inched down to a 75 percent growth rate from 79 percent in 
198287 the far west cooled to 78 percent in the latest 12 
months down from 82 percent 
the plains states southwest and rocky mountain area all 
dependent on either agriculture mining oil drilling or a 
combination all showed improvement but remain at the bottom of 
the list 
income growth in the plains was 62 percent in the 12 months 
ending in june up from 59 percent earlier in the southwest 58 
percent up from 55 percent and in the rocky mountain area 52 
percent up from 51 percent 
the commerce department attributed gains in the great lakes 
states to strength in the manufacturing of durable goods big 
ticket items expected to last three or more years and in 
construction it said the midatlantic region also benefited from a 
pickup in manufacturing 
economists had been anticipating income gains in the 
manufacturing rust belt of the nation the drop in the value of 
the dollar over the last three years has made us goods less 
expensive on overseas markets and has fueled a boom in export sales 
this year 
in a separate report tuesday the federal reserve board said 
virtually every one of its 12 regional banks were reporting 
continued strength or expansion across a wide range of 
manufacturing industries 
however the report prepared for a nov 1 meeting of fed policy 
makers said manufacturers are becoming less optimistic about 
coming months theyve become more cautious about the first half 
of 1989 following a slight slowdown late this summer the report 
said 
although income growth in the southeast as a whole was down 
according to the commerce department by state it was mixed weak 
growth in incomes from service jobs in georgia and interior states 
more than offset strong growth in the atlantic coast states of 
florida north carolina virginia and south carolina 
</TEXT>
