<TEXT>
in the years after it was founded in 
1943 radcliffe colleges arthur and elizabeth schlesinger library 
on the history of women in america was a sleepy place with few 
visitors curators say 
but with its official reopening tuesday after a 35 million 
renovation the library is sleepy no longer after its humble 
beginnings in two small rooms in the basement of a building on the 
radcliffe campus the library now occupies the entire structure 
because of the interest sparked in womens studies by the 
feminist movement the number of visiting researchers now numbers 
about 5000 per year 
the library the only one of its kind in the nation collects 
materials on womens roles and contributions from 1800 to the 
present it includes a collection so varied that one can study 
aviatrix amelia earharts papers research the early womens 
suffrage movement peruse 5000 cookbooks or review former first 
lady eleanor roosevelts book of common sense etiquette 
the redbrick building in radcliffe yard houses rooms for 
visiting scholars film and videotape viewing rooms for oral 
history projects photography exhibits 500 womens 
interestperiodicals a planned wooden relief by sculptress louise 
nevelson and the 5000volume julia child study area named for the 
famed chef 
its like a quantum jump in the recognition that real womens 
issues and history are here to stay said eva moseley curator of 
manuscripts who has been at the library since 1971 
alongside oil portraits of lydia pinkham who marketed a 
wellknown patent remedy for womens illnesses and stained glass 
artist sarah wyman whitman visitors can examine more than 30000 
books that concern women on exhibit are memorabilia from the 
womens suffrage movement rattlers shaken by women in suffrage 
parades banners and placards reading keep cool there will be 
nothing to worry about after we get votes for women 
elizabeth shenton assistant to the library director said the 
library was almost a closet when she began work there 21 years ago 
we were in two little rooms she recalled it was such an 
event when one researcher came that we offered them tea but the 
womens movement increased interest in us so much it just 
ballooned 
the library was launched in 1943 as the womens rights 
collection using papers donated to the college from suffragist maud 
park wood a member of radcliffes class of 1898 
the collection opened to the public in 1949 with 300 books and 
1156 manuscripts in 1965 the library was renamed to honor 
harvard history professor schlesinger and his wife who was a 
historian of women and active in the league of women voters their 
son historian arthur jr has said that his mother raised my 
fathers consciousness 
in later years the library began to focus on the contributions 
women have made to domestic life an exhibit of etiquette books 
such as no nice girls swear is on display 
one of the most unusual collections consists of cookbooks from 
the 1800s to the present stacked in shelves near a huge blownup 
photograph of child her papers are also part of the library 
gina deangelis 25 a thirdyear student at boston university 
law school was at the library tuesday researching womens unions 
in the 1940s for a legal history class 
this is the only library where i could find this material 
she said 
museum staffer nancy falk said that for years women studying at 
colleges in the area were unaware of the librarys existence 
all of sudden though women are a legitimate field of 
study she said 
the renovation of the existing 1908 building was financed by 
more than 3500 gifts and grants 
</TEXT>
