a technician who plugged a connector 
into the wrong receptacle caused a flash electrical fire that did 
minor damage to the 216 million magellan venus probe being readied 
for a space shuttle launch next year nasa reported tuesday 
smoke and a 2to3inch flame spurted from a spacecraft battery 
when the worker tried to insert the cable connector into the wrong 
slot monday night magellan project official vince wirth said 
technicians on the scene quickly put out the fire within a 
minute with a halon fire extinguisher wirth said but by then 
the damage was done it resulted in a short that damaged the 
battery and wire harness and insulation blankets near the battery 
he termed the damage minor and estimated it would take five to 
seven days to get spacecraft preparation back on schedule he said 
there would be no impact on the april launch date aboard the 
shuttle atlantis 
wirth played a videotape made tuesday that showed some soot 
damage around the battery area the battery he explained was 
being used to run routine power system checks in the spacecrafts 
forward equipment module and is not part of the flight hardware 
he said the fire deposited some soot grease and grime on 
parts of the spacecraft and that it would have to be cleaned up he 
said magellan because of its planetary mission has to be kept 
extremely contaminationfree and that cleaning experts were being 
flown in from nasas jet propulsion laboratory in pasadena calif 
and from martin marietta in denver where the craft was built 
because an electrical short was involved wirth said engineers 
were checking to make certain there was no damage to other 
electrical components such as the spacecraft signal processor 
in washington nasa administrator james c fletcher told 
reporters apparently the wrong plug was put in the power supply 
i dont know whether you ever tried to put a multipronged plug 
into a socket but its hard to do it wouldnt fit so he pushed 
it a little bit and it shorted out the battery 
we shouldnt allow this kind of stuff fletcher added 
its a human error well have an investigation and take some 
steps so it wont happen in the future 
wirth said the technician who made the mistake worked for martin 
marietta which delivered magellan here on oct 8 the spacecraft 
is being assembled and checked in a processing building when fully 
assembled the craft will stand 21 feet tall and weigh 7800 pounds 
wirth said because of the recent delivery many electrical 
components still had not been installed reducing the possibility 
of more damage and several protective shipping covers were still 
in place cutting down on the spread of soot 
atlantis astronaut crew is to release the spacecraft from the 
cargo bay to start it on a 446day trip to venus while magellan 
orbits the planet its advanced radar will peer through the 
constant clouds and map the surface 
before that mission atlantis has another flight assignment it 
is being readied here for a late november launch in which it is to 
carry a classified defense department payload into orbit a problem 
with an actuator that controls the left wing flap has delayed for a 
few days its transfer from a processing facility to an assembly 
building where it will be joined with its two solid fuel booster 
rockets and external fuel tank 
a firm launch date will not be set until a flight readiness 
review scheduled nov 9 and 10 
the flight will be the second for the shuttle program since the 
challenger explosion in january 1986 discovery completed a highly 
successful mission on oct 3 and is now being groomed for a 
february launch 
