rightwing christian legislators 
boycotted a voting session that was to elect a new speaker of 
parliament tuesday and a lawmaker said his colleagues were 
dancing on the grave of lebanon 
the failure to elect a successor to hussein husseini a shiite 
moslem whose oneyear term ended sunday sparked a new feud between 
christians and moslems 
in the absence of the 39member quorum required to extend 
husseinis term or elect a new speaker the 26 moslem deputies who 
showed up for the voting session declared husseini a caretaker 
speaker until a successor can be elected 
the christian deputies countered by issuing a statement 
rejecting husseini a staunch ally of syria and naming their own 
speaker pro tempore kazem khalil 88 the eldest deputy among the 
76 members of parliament 
this is the fatal blow said khalil a westernoriented 
shiite who lives in christian east beirut were actually dancing 
on the grave in which we have buried lebanon 
lebanon has been without a head of state since president amin 
gemayels sixyear term ended sept 22 and no successor was elected 
because parliament could not gather the necessary quorum 
two rival governments one moslem and one christian have since 
emerged splitting the army and security forces along religious 
lines 
newly arrived us ambassador john mccarthy made his first visit 
to the foreign ministry tuesday apparently to smooth tensions 
after he was criticized by the ministrys director general farouk 
abillamaa for not presenting his credentials to the christian 
government of army commander gen michel aoun 
