<TEXT>
the next president will have to take 
major steps to turn around an economy destabilized by an entrenched 
budget deficit and policy flaws say economic advisers of varying 
political stripes in a harvard business review report 
in a set of eight papers experts from consumer activist ralph 
nader to nobel laureate paul samuelson offer the next president 
economic advice amid a presidential campaign that the magazine says 
has produced a lot of partisan noisiness but little serious 
deliberation 
theres a fundamental basic instability in the economic system 
right now harvard business review editor theodore levitt said 
monday summing up the papers 
the magazine had asked panel members to write memos advising the 
next president on a range of economic issues the 42page report 
will appear in the magazines novemberdecember issue 
the underlying conclusion a fundamental instability in the us 
economic system needs to be addressed indeed the federal budget 
deficit is so deeply rooted that it wont solve itself in the 
normal course of economic events 
samuelson a massachusetts institute of technology professor 
emeritus argues that fear of alienating voters has frightened 
away all candidates from even discussing vital economic issues 
the new president he says should spend his first year trying 
to reduce the deficit from about 3 percent of the nations 4 
trillion gross national product toward 2 percent and ultimately 
by 1992 eliminating all deficit that isnt cyclical 
a basic structural deficit is one that exists regardless of 
prevailing economic conditions so that public debt rises even 
after the nation returns to full employment cyclical deficits are 
tied to inflation unemployment and other economic conditions 
when asked how to tame a basic deficit one might answer 
prosaically by expenditure cuts and tax increases but 
samuelson says the new president needs to abandon the notion that 
the deficit can be reduced by either cutting spending or raising 
taxes or a 5050 combination 
the experts two of whom advise the presidential candidates 
democrat michael dukakis and republican george bush offer 
detailed advice for increasing capital formation modernizing the 
nations manufacturing base and overhauling public education 
tell the american people the truth that todays apparent 
prosperity is being borrowed from the future that our children 
will be angry and frustrated when they are left with a lower 
standard of living advises clyde v prestowitz jr a former 
counselor for japan affairs to the secretary of commerce 
nader a thorn in the side of big business for 25 years 
surprisingly argues that government can learn from business to 
become more efficient humane creative and responsive 
the next president should break through the legendary oval 
office cocoon to communicate regularly and directly with federal 
workers he says he should visit major departments mix it up 
with the employees listen to their ideas stimulate their thinking 
and remind them of the importance of their mission 
conservative economist martin feldstein a bush adviser 
counsels avoiding protectionist policies that some industries may 
press for during the long road back to trade balance 
if you accede to these pressures you would not only hurt 
american consumers and weaken the competitiveness of american 
industry but would also risk the start of a protectionist trade 
