<TEXT>
new york says it will place a higher 
wihholding tax on bonuses commissions and other supplemental wages 
to make it harder for those in the financial services industry to 
evade taxes 
the state department of taxation and finance announced monday 
that starting jan 1 new york will hike its withholding tax to 
7875 percent from 5 percent on supplemental income sources unless 
taxpayers make prior arrangements to have withholding taxes figured 
at the same rate as regular wages 
state tax commissioner james wetzler said the change stems from 
a tax department investigation that turned up thousands of tax 
evaders at prominent wall street brokerages and investment houses 
including employees at drexel burnham lambert inc bear stearns amp 
co and shearson lehman hutton inc 
when arrests were made of some toplevel employees of those 
businesses in april former tax commissioner roderick chu said 
state officials were numbed and shocked at how widespread the 
tax cheating had become on wall street at that time chu said the 
state had found more than 5700 income tax evaders including 1519 
people with salaries of more than 50000 a year 
the probe revealed that many brokers and investment counselors 
were properly paying state income taxes on their regular salaries 
but they were found to be paying the 5 percent withholding tax and 
no more on the bonuses partnership distributions and other 
supplemental income they were receiving 
in many cases said tax department spokesman paul rickard 
nonsalary income is far larger than the regular pay the executives 
get 
rickard said he had no estimate of how much in taxes experts 
feel the state is getting cheated out of in that manner 
according to wetzler the changes on bonus and commission 
withholding is expected to bring the state about 55 million more 
in the fiscal year ending march 31 1989 and 90 million more in 
the fiscal year beginning the next day 
tax officials said the state has now matched a list of employees 
of 1100 banks investment firms and stock brokerages with a list 
of people not filing income tax returns rickard said 10000 
warning letters will be mailed by the tax department this week to 
people the state suspects of not properly filing returns 
according to the spokesman the state is continuing the process 
of settling accounts with those taxpayers found to be shortchanging 
the state this spring 
he said tax officials are expanding their probe to other fields 
where some workers earn big bonuses or commissions such as real 
