<TEXT>
this midwestern city once recognized 
nationally for the swift emergence of health maintenance 
organizations is now at the center of an industrywide shakeout 
the merger of four tulsa health care plans within a few months 
represents a growing national trend of consolidation among hmos 
it sounds like a western but this towns not big enough for 
more plans said dr cb rebsamen of prucare of tulsa one of 
three surviving health maintenance plans left in a city that once 
offered more than 20 
i think whats happening in tulsa is an example of what the 
rest of the country is experiencing said rebsamen who is head 
of the doctor group for prucare we seem to be experiencing the 
end of the boost in the industry 
hmos which emerged earlier this decade as an alternative to 
traditional health insurance are prepaid plans of health services 
that include preventive treatment 
the plans buoyed by federal legislation requiring many 
employers to provide hmos as an option to employees offer health 
services through physician groups controlled by hmo units 
independent groups or private physicians who agree to participate 
industry observers say the large number of insolvencies and 
repeated annual losses for hmos are due to the rapid expansion in 
the industry rising benefit costs undercapitalization 
mismanagement and tough competition 
what theyre suffering most from is shortsightedness and 
stupidity said peter boland president of boland healthcare 
consultants in berkeley calif a national consulting firm for 
managed health plans 
as much as twothirds of all hmos nationally reported losses in 
1987 more than any other previous year boland said 
hmos have faced the added pressure of the evolution of preferred 
provider organizations or ppos another threeletter plan that in 
many cases offers customers more flexibility choice and 
accessibility than the traditional hmo boland said 
the combined effect of financial instability and viable 
competition in the market made initial early growth for hmos a 
shortlived phenomenon he said 
it really flew in the face of dynamics that are coming back to 
haunt them boland said 
bluelincs hmo in tulsa a blue cross and blue shield group 
acquired hmo of oklahoma health accord of oklahoma and aetna 
choice healthcare plan all within four months 
a unification of four hmos in less than 120 days is 
unprecedented in this industry said tom bowser executive vice 
president of bluelincs when announcing the last acquisition this 
past summer 
the tulsa mergers were not included in the most recent national 
quarterly report issued by interstudy a nonprofit research group 
based in excelsior minn that studies the health maintenance 
industry but the activity has not gone unnoticed said senior 
interstudy researcher judith hale 
theres certainly a trend toward consolidation nationally 
ms hale said youre either going to have to grow or youre going 
to have to go with a larger plan 
in 1985 tulsa began to be recognized by health care experts as 
an example of the growth and expansion of hmos across the country 
in that year 11 plans were offered in the city of 380000 
few medical markets outside california and minneapolis are as 
highly competitive and its doubtful any became so as fast 
wrote larry frederick senior associate editor of medical 
economics in the may 1985 issue of the national health industry 
magazine 
in 1985 there were 480 hmo plans nationwide with 21 million 
members the number of plans and participants had grown steadily 
since 1981 with the largest increase in plans and enrollment in 
1985 
we set up a situation where it was pretty easy to get into the 
hmo business ms hale said but its not very easy to stay in 
its a tough business 
hmos that succeed will have excellent management will be 
diversified and may or may not be legally constituted as hmos 
she states in a report on the future of the industry 
with the termination of physicians health plan of oklahoma only 
three plans remain in tulsa serving nearly 90000 clients 
nationally 15 health plans not including those merged in 
tulsa were terminated merged or acquired by another group in the 
first quarter of 1988 according to interstudy 
ms hale said national studies indicate a decrease in growth in 
the hmo industry with fewer new plans started and a drop in 
enrollment growth last year was the first year since 1981 that 
enrollment did not increase from the previous year and the first 
quarter of 1988 shows a decrease in the number of plans according 
to interstudys statistics 
as of march there were 648 hmos in the country serving 31 
million members an increase of 17 million clients since the 
previous quarter ms hale said the growth seemed to peak in june 
1987 with 662 plans serving just under 29 million members she said 
theres no question that the growth rate is slowing but its 
hardly a dying industry when you see 17 million new members she 
said what we see now is the number of new plans is balanced with 
the number of merged plans 
</TEXT>
