<TEXT>
hercules inc on tuesday introduced a new 
filmpackaging technology that it claimed will double the shelf 
life of fresh produce 
hercules said its new freshhold package system controls the 
atmosphere inside packages thereby keeping produce fresh longer 
and preserving its appearance taste and color 
hercules a chemical and aerospace company based in wilmington 
del said it took five years to develop the packaging 
the key element is a breathable film that allows fresh produce 
to continue breathing after packing james e knox president of 
hercules engineered polymers co told a news conference this 
breathable film regulates the rate at which oxygen and carbon 
dioxide enter and leave the package 
an initial venture involving broccoli has been successful knox 
said 
freshhold packaging has been testmarketed at supermarkets in 
richmond va baltimore chicago los angeles minneapolis and 
dallas 
cauliflower strawberries celery carrots lettuce and 
pineapple will be available with the new packaging next year the 
company said 
while packaged produce now makes up only 3 percent of the 
billiondollar us produce market many companies are working on 
similar concepts to extend shelf life experts say the new product 
also will reduce the amount of ice needed to transport produce 
across the country 
the freshhold packaging also has some drawbacks according to 
experts the lunglike membrane on top of the film has to be custom 
designed to the respiration rate of each type of produce held in 
the box and it requires good refrigeration for optimum performance 
in addition consumers must be convinced that precut fruits and 
vegetables are as fresh as those they can choose themselves from 
the produce bin the experts say the produce packaged in freshhold 
sells for slightly more than unpackaged fruits and vegetables 
</TEXT>
