<TEXT>
after serving two years as president of troubled 
burger king charles s olcott resigned tuesday in the fastfood 
companys second top management shakeup this year 
the resignation comes as burger kings parent minneapolisbased 
pillsbury co is scrambling to defend itself against an unwanted 
takeover bid 
analysts said it was olcotts failure to reverse burger kings 
losing trend that led to his departure under olcott burger king 
embarked on an expensive and ultimately disappointing marketing 
campaign based on the slogan we do it like youd do it 
william maguire an analyst at merrill lynch amp co in new york 
said olcott wasnt a marketing man when they needed a marketing 
man badly 
pillsbury is in the process of defending itself against an 
unsolicited 523 billion tender offer launched by londonbased 
grand metropolitan plc 
analysts speculated that pillsbury might opt to sell burger 
king the worlds secondlargest hamburger chain in an effort to 
preserve its independence a sale could bring as much as 2 billion 
pillsburys board unanimously rejected grand mets 60ashare 
offer tuesday calling it inadequate and not in the best 
interests of the company and its shareholders 
theyre fighting the only battle they can said john 
mcmillin an analyst with prudentialbache securities inc in new 
york 
the hamburger chain accounts for about onethird of pillsburys 
sales and about twothirds of its profits but has not done well 
recently its pretax profits have decline by more than 50 percent 
from 1192 million in fiscal 1986 to 482 million for the year 
ended may 31 the company reported 
pillsbury chairman philip l smith said tuesday in urging 
shareholders to reject grand mets bid that significant investments 
have been made to improve burger king operations he said improved 
performance is critical to the chain 
olcotts departure marks yet another major management shakeup 
for the fastfood chain which has had five chairman and eight 
presidents since pillsbury took over in 1967 
most recently j jeffery campbell resigned as head of 
pillsburys ailing restaurant group in june 
jerry w levin a pillsbury executive vice president was named 
burger kings chairman he had worked previously in mergers and 
acquisitions at pillsbury prompting financial analysts to 
speculate pillsbury might be preparing to get rid of the 
miamibased restaurant chain 
the guys good at doing deals mcmillin said ive got to 
think hes been brought in to do a deal 
